				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				DT, how can you balance the examples of a fictional place and fictional characters, to real life ones?  That's hardly an argument.  Simple solution, NO ONE was intentinally hurt or misrepresented in ANY way.  However, doing so in real life will equate to a law suit and possibly jail time.<BR>
<BR>
You say no one can debate with you, or at least the person you were referring to.  So I wonder if you can debate real life versus science fiction and fantasy.<BR>
<BR>
There are many Internet News Groups that you can obtain any story pertaining to whatever genre that fits your fancy.  However, seeking legal defense against all these amateur fictional authors would be a true waste of time, money and resources.  <BR>
<BR>
On the other hand, doing something evil as portrayed in this fiction in real life, equates to many real life consequences, which could also include a death penalty if your state so supports that.  So tell me, how can you come up with a rational debate from real life, to science fiction/fantasy.  I am eager to hear it.<BR>
<BR>
You are correct in the statement that Verant has a right to do whatever they want.  However, does it pass the ethic's committee when they do it?  Probably not.  Will it affect their customer base as a whole, probably.  Does it affect me, yes.  Although I won't quit the game because of this, believe me when I say if it wasn't for the guild that I was currently in, or the friends that interract with me on this basis, there would be no reason to be there.  The game at this point, is simply boring to me.<BR>
<BR>
However I think some of us have lost their sight to the realism, since you wish to remain in that topic.  It's a GAME.  If Verant were concerned about copyright infringement, they should look at all the other fan fiction, despite the fact that this one particular document they did not agree with, it doesn't make it right that they demand retribution in the way of banning this person.  All you have done, is make an enemy.<BR>
<BR>
Let's not forget the rule of good customer service.  It takes 10 years to make 1 good customer, and only 10 minutes to lose them.<BR>
<BR>
-Celtic Troll<BR>
<BR>
Oh, and please email me if you wish to follow through with a debate.  Although I don't feel it will get either of us anywhere, if it will make you feel better please do.
